Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is tokenization in NLP?
AI Response

Tokenization splits text into smaller units (tokens) such as words, subwords, or characters. Subword
tokenization (BPE, WordPiece) balances vocabulary size with handling of rare words.

Example 1.2

User

What is GPT?
AI Response

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is an autoregressive language model trained to predict the next
token. GPT-3 and GPT-4 are large-scale versions capable of diverse language tasks.

Example 1.3

User

What is attention mechanism?
AI Response

Attention allows a model to focus on relevant input parts during output generation. Self-attention in
transformers computes weighted relationships between all token pairs.

Example 1.4

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.5

User

What is the ROC curve?
AI Response

The ROC curve plots true positive rate vs false positive rate at various thresholds. AUC (Area Under Curve)
summarizes performance—a perfect model has AUC = 1.0.

Example 1.6

User

What is overfitting?
AI Response

Overfitting occurs when a model learns training data too well—including noise—causing poor generalization
to new data. Symptoms include high train accuracy but low validation accuracy.

Example 1.7

User

What is precision vs recall?
AI Response



Precision is correct positive predictions / all positive predictions. Recall is correct positive predictions / all
actual positives. F1 score harmonically balances both.

Example 1.8

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.9

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response

Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.

Example 1.10

User

What is the vanishing gradient problem?
AI Response

In deep networks, gradients shrink exponentially during backpropagation, preventing early layers from
learning. Solutions include ReLU activations, residual connections, and LSTMs.



